    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading a manual for a cessna and it mentioned the pitot tube. can u explain how it actually works to measure airspeed and why it's so important?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The pitot tube measures airspeed by sensing the difference between the total pressure (ram air pressure) and the static pressure around the aircraft. It's essentially a pressure sensor that tells the aircraft's instruments how fast it's moving through the air. This is vital because airspeed directly dictates flight characteristics, allowing pilots to maintain safe speeds for takeoff, cruise, and landing. Without it, the pilot would have no reliable way to know if they are flying too fast or too slow.",
      "source": "target",
