    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. i also saw a section about how blockages can mess up the readings. what kind of stuff usually gets stuck in there and causes issues?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Blockages in the pitot tube are a serious issue, usually caused by foreign objects or environmental factors. Common culprits include insects, ice, snow, or even debris kicked up by the aircraft. When these things block the opening, the instrument receives an inaccurate reading, often showing zero airspeed or a dangerously low reading, which is a critical hazard. It's always important to inspect and keep these tubes clear, especially before flight.",
      "source": "target",
