    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "so if it's just something small like an insect or dirt, how much of a problem is it really? like does a tiny blockage actually change the pressure enough to make the airspeed reading totally wrong?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Even a seemingly tiny blockage can cause a significant and dangerous deviation in the airspeed reading. Because the pitot tube relies on a precise pressure differential, even a small obstruction can impede the flow of fast-moving air, effectively choking the reading. This can lead to a false indication of slow speed, which could cause a pilot to react incorrectly in a critical phase of flight. It's better to treat any suspected blockage as a major problem, as the margin for error is very slim.",
